{
 "title": "SWE-chat: Coding Agent Interactions From Real Users in the Wild",
 "core_contribution": "SWE-chat is the first large-scale dataset of real, in-the-wild coding-agent sessions from open-source developers who opted into the Entire.io CLI, which checkpoints AI-assisted coding sessions and pushes session logs to public GitHub branches. It pairs the FULL agent transcript (user prompts, assistant replies, every tool call and tool result, token usage, timestamps) with the resulting git history (commits, diffs, patches) plus line-level human-vs-agent code authorship attribution. This lets one measure what fraction of agent output survives into commits, classify collaboration modes, and study real user behavior (intents, pushback, personas). It is positioned as a living/growing dataset with an automatic discovery pipeline. Scale at the analyzed snapshot: ~5,851 sessions, 2.69M conversation turns, 63K+ user prompts, 355K+ tool calls, 14,459 commits, 13,406 checkpoints, 205 repositories.",
 "methodology": "See methodology field above.",
 "metrics": [
  {
   "name": "agent_percentage",
   "definition": "Per-session percentage (0-100) of committed lines authored by the agent; the basis for collaboration-mode classification. Derived from agent_lines vs human_added/human_modified/human_removed over total_committed."
  },
  {
   "name": "Collaboration mode (3-way)",
   "definition": "Human-only = 0% agent-authored committed lines (22.7% of sessions); Collaborative = agent authors >0% but <99% (36.5%); Vibe coding = agent authors >99% (40.8%). Mutually exclusive, computed from agent_percentage."
  },
  {
   "name": "Agent code survival rate",
   "definition": "Fraction of agent-produced code that survives into committed code; reported as ~44% survive (44.3% discarded before commit)."
  },
  {
   "name": "User pushback rate",
   "definition": "Fraction of turns where the user corrects/rejects/reports failure/interrupts; reported ~39-44% of turns."
  },
  {
   "name": "Tokens per committed line",
   "definition": "Cost-efficiency metric; vibe coding uses ~3x more tokens per committed line than collaborative (the most cost-efficient mode)."
  },
  {
   "name": "Security findings per 1K lines",
   "definition": "Semgrep vulnerability findings introduced per 1,000 committed lines; vibe-coded 0.76 vs human-only 0.08 (~9x)."
  },
  {
   "name": "session_success",
   "definition": "LLM-annotated success score 0-100 (stored as string) per session."
  },
  {
   "name": "prompt_intent distribution",
   "definition": "Per-prompt intent label; understand 19.0%, create 13.4%, git 13.4%, debug 13.0%, other 26.6%; refactor/test/connect less frequent."
  }
 ],
 "task_or_data_design": "Relational dataset, 6 HF configs each a single 'train' split (no train/val/test split): conversations (2,692,480 rows), sessions (5,851), session_logs (5,851), checkpoints (13,406), commits (14,459), repositories (205). Files: conversations.parquet (1.31GB), commits.parquet (1.08GB), checkpoints.parquet (5.56MB), session_logs.parquet (6.37MB), sessions.parquet (2MB), repositories.parquet (245kB), plus a transcripts/ folder and README.md (21kB). License: ODC-BY (Open Data Commons Attribution) on HF; the project website states CC BY 4.0 and the GitHub repo states MIT (license is inconsistent across sources). Agents represented: ~85% Claude Code, remainder OpenCode/Gemini CLI/Cursor/Factory AI Droid/Codex. session_logs holds full context.md and raw metadata.json per session; sessions carries token totals, tool-call counts, files_touched (JSON), duration_seconds, user_persona, session_success, agent_percentage and authorship line counts. repositories carries repo_type_domain (application/library/devtools/other), repo_type_audience (enduser/developer/researchers/education), license_type, and all-time vs in-dataset commit/addition stats.",
 "key_findings": [
  "Only ~44% of agent-produced code survives into user commits (44.3% discarded before committing).",
  "Collaboration modes shifted over the ~3-month window: vibe-coding share roughly doubled from ~20% to >40% of sessions.",
  "Vibe coding is ~3x more token-expensive per committed line; collaborative coding is the most cost-efficient mode.",
  "Vibe-coded commits introduce ~9x more security vulnerabilities per 1K lines than human-only (0.76 vs 0.08 Semgrep findings).",
  "Users push back in ~39-44% of turns (corrections, rejections, failure reports, interruptions); agents proactively ask for clarification in only ~1.1-2.6% of turns.",
  "Even in vibe coding, ~47% of users still act as detailed reviewers ('expert nitpicker' persona).",
  "Top user intent is understanding existing code (19.0%), not writing new code."
 ],
 "reusable_for_usersimbench": [
  "The conversations turn schema is a ready-made user-turn taxonomy backbone: prompt_intent {create/refactor/debug/understand/connect/git/test/other} and prompt_pushback {correction/rejection/failure_report/pacing_complaint/takeover/requirement_change/non_pushback} give a labeled distribution of real user turn types to sample/condition a simulator on.",
  "user_persona labels {Expert Nitpicker, Vague Requester, Mind Changer, Other} provide ready persona archetypes for a user simulator, with empirical mode-conditioned priors (e.g. vibe coding ~47% nitpicker, ~5% mind changer).",
  "Collaboration-mode definition via agent_percentage thresholds (0% / >0-<99% / >99%) is a directly reusable, simple outcome label for stratifying simulated sessions.",
  "The checkpoint join layer (session<->checkpoint<->commit) plus per-file file_attribution and full `patch` diffs gives ground-truth for evaluating whether a simulated user's accept/reject/correction behavior matches real diff-survival outcomes (44% survival benchmark).",
  "is_conversational + turn_type flags let you reconstruct clean user/assistant dialogue while still having tool_use/tool_result context \u2014 useful for building simulator training/eval transcripts.",
  "Token-usage fields (input/output/cache_creation/cache_read) and duration_seconds enable cost/efficiency metrics for a simulator-driven agent harness.",
  "session_success (0-100 LLM-annotated) is a reusable outcome label for grading simulated sessions.",
  "PII pipeline recipe (Presidio SpaCy NER + TruffleHog) is reusable for sanitizing any user-turn corpus."
 ],
 "relevance": "Directly central to UserSimBench: this is real, schema-rich human user behavior paired with agent transcripts and ground-truth git outcomes. It supplies (a) an empirical taxonomy of user-turn types and pushback, (b) persona archetypes with mode-conditioned priors, (c) measurable downstream outcomes (diff survival, success score, collaboration mode) to validate a user simulator against, and (d) a clean relational schema to mirror. It is the strongest available empirical backbone for grounding and evaluating simulated users.",
 "uncertainties": [
  "LICENSE CONFLICT: HF dataset card says ODC-BY; project website summary says CC BY 4.0; GitHub repo says MIT. The actual HF metadata (odc-by) is most authoritative for the data, but this should be confirmed before redistribution.",
  "The exact arXiv ID 2604.20779 and date (April 22, 2026) come from fetched pages; the future-dated id format is unusual \u2014 verify the id resolves.",
  "Line-level human-vs-agent attribution ALGORITHM is NOT disclosed in the paper (only that Entire.io computes it via agent author-pattern matching); agent_percentage internals are opaque.",
  "The conversations table prompt_pushback enumerates 7 values (correction/rejection/failure_report/pacing_complaint/takeover/requirement_change/non_pushback) while the paper text describes only ~4 (correction/rejection/failure report/non-pushback). The 7-value schema came from a fast-model read of the dataset card and should be confirmed against actual parquet values.",
  "Exact collaboration-mode percentages (22.7/36.5/40.8) and the >99% vibe threshold are consistently reported, but whether 'human-only' means exactly 0% agent lines vs a small epsilon was inferred from '>0%' collaborative boundary; confirm.",
  "Some per-row column names (e.g. queue_op_subtype, bash_category, category taxonomy values) were read from the dataset card by a fast model; verify against the real parquet headers before coding against them.",
  "The 'transcripts/' folder contents/format were not inspected (likely raw JSONL session logs referenced by session_logs.transcript_path) \u2014 confirm by listing that folder.",
  "Total counts vary by source/snapshot (website says 6K+ sessions / 2.7M interactions; HF says 5,851 sessions / 2,692,480 conversation rows) because it is a living dataset \u2014 pin to a specific HF revision."
 ],
 "authors": "Joachim Baumann, Vishakh Padmakumar, Xiang Li, John Yang, Diyi Yang, Sanmi Koyejo (Stanford SALT-NLP and collaborators)",
 "venue_or_date": "arXiv:2604.20779, preprint dated April 22, 2026 (cs.AI / cs.SE / cs.CY)"
}

{
 "title": "Mind the Sim2Real Gap in User Simulation for Agentic Tasks",
 "authors": "Xuhui Zhou, Weiwei Sun, Qianou Ma, Yiqing Xie, Jiarui Liu, Weihua Du, Sean Welleck, Yiming Yang, Graham Neubig, Sherry Tongshuang Wu, Maarten Sap (CMU LTI and collaborators)",
 "venue_or_date": "arXiv:2603.11245 (cs.AI), v1 submitted ~March 11, 2026",
 "core_contribution": "First large-scale human-grounded study of the Sim2Real gap in LLM user simulators for agentic (tool-using customer-service) tasks. The authors run the full tau-bench protocol with 451 real human participants over 165 tasks (50 airline + 115 retail) against a fixed agent, then benchmark 31 LLM user simulators against those humans. They introduce the User-Sim Index (USI), a single 0-100 composite measuring how well a simulator reproduces real human interactive BEHAVIOR (4 behavioral dimensions), OUTCOME calibration (success-rate calibration), and EVALUATIVE alignment (post-interaction survey ratings). Best simulator (DeepSeek-V3.1) scores USI=76.0 vs human-human ceiling 92.9, revealing a large gap: simulators are an \"easy mode\" (over-cooperative, stylistically uniform, front-load info, lack uncertainty/frustration, pivot instead of pushing back), which inflates agent success rates and which LLM-judges further over-rate.",
 "methodology": "USI construction (reimplementation-grade):\n\nUSI aggregates three families of signals into a 0-100 score.\n- With both behavioral and evaluative signals: USI = (1/6)(D1 + D2 + D3 + D4 + (1-ECE)*100 + Eval)\n- With only behavioral signals (no survey for that simulator): USI = (1/5)(D1 + D2 + D3 + D4 + (1-ECE)*100)\nwhere each of D1-D4 is already on a 0-100 scale, ECE is in [0,1], and Eval=(1-MAE)*100.\n\nBehavioral dimensions D1-D4 (each is the mean of several lexical/structural metrics extracted from transcripts; humans are the reference distribution):\n- D1 Communication Style: politeness/formality (LIWC2015 lexicon), verbosity variation, identity confusion (regex). E.g. only 1.0% of GPT-4o turns are brief vs 29.0% for humans; 49.0% of GPT-4o turns polite vs 15.3% human.\n- D2 Information Pattern: front-loading ratio and identifier density (regex over high-entropy tokens, e.g. order IDs). E.g. UserLM-8b emits ~4.8 IDs/turn vs 2.6 for humans.\n- D3 Clarification: uncertainty/certainty/hedging markers (LIWC). E.g. GPT-4o hedges in 14.6% of turns vs 7.3% human.\n- D4 Error Reaction: emotion/frustration (NRC Word-Emotion lexicon), accusatory language, strategy pivoting. Simulators pivot strategy in ~16.5-19.1% of error turns vs 8.4% human.\nEach metric m is matched to humans via a Sorensen-Dice-style ratio: Dice_m = 2*min(M_m, H_m)/(M_m + H_m) * 100, where M_m is the simulator's value and H_m the human value. Dimension score = mean Dice over its constituent metrics; reported as mean+/-std across the 3 annotation batches.\n\nOutcome calibration (ECE): tasks are binned (by difficulty), and ECE = sum_b (|S_b|/N) * |p_sim(b) - p_human(b)|, i.e. the weighted average absolute gap between simulator success rate and human success rate per bin. Success = automatic tau-bench reward (binary, based on final database state matching the success criteria). (1-ECE)*100 enters USI.\n\nEvaluative alignment (Eval): for each survey field, compute per-task absolute error between simulator-condition and human ratings (normalized to [0,1]); take per-task MAE across survey fields within a batch, average per batch, then mean+/-std across batches. Eval=(1-MAE)*100.\n\nComparison protocol: keep the AGENT and the REWARD FUNCTION identical and only swap the user (human vs LLM simulator), isolating the effect of user realism. Primary agent = GPT-5.2 (robustness check with Gemini-3.1-Pro in appendix). Three independent annotation batches on the same 165 tasks (distinct annotator groups each) give a human-human agreement ceiling (USI=92.9) against which simulators are scored.\n\nHuman study protocol: participants recruited from Prolific (general adult pool, ages 18-80, median 37; ~51% male/44% female; ~89% English primary). Each participant is given a task instruction sheet (customer goal + constraints + role-play guidelines) and role-plays the customer in a web chat UI: side panel shows the task/role-play guidelines, main panel is turn-by-turn chat, intermediate agent reasoning/tool traces are visible, and the participant types /stop to end and trigger the post-task survey. The post-interaction survey collects ~8 quality dimensions (task success 5-way; efficiency; question amount; answer effort; human-likeness; interaction flow; overall performance 1-5; reuse intent), plus open-text behavioral examples / improvement suggestions in the released dataset. 451 participants produced 495 annotated conversations = 3 batches x 165 tasks; consistent with roughly one interaction per participant. Quality control: each annotation has an LLM-generated quality_score (0-100), quality_passed flag, llm_reasoning, optional human review, and a keep flag.",
 "metrics": [
  {
   "name": "User-Sim Index (USI)",
   "definition": "0-100 composite of how closely an LLM user simulator matches real humans. USI=(1/6)(D1+D2+D3+D4+(1-ECE)*100+Eval) when evaluative signals exist, else (1/5)(D1+D2+D3+D4+(1-ECE)*100). Human-human ceiling 92.9; best simulator (DeepSeek-V3.1) 76.0; GPT-5.1 70.9."
  },
  {
   "name": "D1 Communication Style",
   "definition": "0-100 Dice-matched score over politeness/formality (LIWC), verbosity variation, identity-confusion (regex) vs human distribution."
  },
  {
   "name": "D2 Information Pattern",
   "definition": "0-100 Dice score over front-loading ratio and identifier-token density per turn vs humans."
  },
  {
   "name": "D3 Clarification",
   "definition": "0-100 Dice score over uncertainty/certainty/hedging marker rates (LIWC) vs humans."
  },
  {
   "name": "D4 Error Reaction",
   "definition": "0-100 Dice score over frustration/emotion (NRC lexicon), accusatory language, and strategy-pivot rate on agent-error turns vs humans."
  },
  {
   "name": "Per-metric Sorensen-Dice",
   "definition": "Dice_m = 2*min(M_m,H_m)/(M_m+H_m)*100, matching simulator metric value M_m to human value H_m; dimension score is the mean over its metrics."
  },
  {
   "name": "ECE (outcome calibration)",
   "definition": "Expected Calibration Error: sum_b (|S_b|/N)*|p_sim(b)-p_human(b)|, the bin-weighted absolute gap between simulator and human tau-bench success rates. (1-ECE)*100 enters USI."
  },
  {
   "name": "Eval (evaluative alignment)",
   "definition": "Eval=(1-MAE)*100, where MAE is the mean absolute error between simulator-condition and human survey ratings (normalized to [0,1]), averaged per task/field/batch."
  },
  {
   "name": "Agent success rate (tau-bench reward)",
   "definition": "Binary task-success reward from tau-bench based on final database state. Human baseline 63.6%; many LLM simulators inflate to as high as 77.8%."
  }
 ],
 "task_or_data_design": "Tasks come from tau-bench customer-service: airline (booking, cancellation, modification) and retail (order management, returns, product inquiries). 165 unique tasks used (50 airline + 115 retail). Released dataset (HuggingFace cmu-lti/tau-usi) is a single file tau_bench_tasks_unified.json with 495 annotated conversations (3 independent batches x 165 tasks; 451 participants). Per-record fields: task_id; instance_id (e.g. airline_0, retail_42_ann2); agent_id (agent model used); conversation (full multi-turn transcript); survey (~8-10 evaluation dimensions, ordinal); quality_score (0-100), quality_passed (bool), llm_reasoning, optional human_score/human_reasoning; keep (post-filter retention); reward (binary tau-bench evaluation signal). 31 LLM simulators benchmarked: ~18 proprietary (GPT-3.5-turbo/4o/4o-mini/5-mini/5/5.1; Claude-3-Haiku/3.5-Sonnet/3.7-Sonnet/4.5-Haiku/Sonnet-4/Opus-4; Gemini-2.0-Flash/2.5-Flash/2.5-Flash-Lite/3-Flash/3-Pro/3.1-Pro), ~9 open-source (DeepSeek-V3.1, Llama-3.3-70B, Llama-4-Maverick, Qwen2.5-7B, Qwen3-235B, Qwen3-Next-80B, GPT-oss-120B, MiniMax-M2.5, Kimi-K2.5), and ~4 specialized user-simulator models (CoSER-8B, UserLM-8B, HumanLike-7B, HumanLM-opinion).",
 "key_findings": [
  "Large Sim2Real gap: best LLM simulator USI=76.0 (DeepSeek-V3.1) vs human-human ceiling 92.9; GPT-5.1=70.9. Stronger general capability does not imply better user simulation.",
  "Simulators are 'easy mode' and inflate agent success: human baseline agent success 63.6%, but most general-purpose simulators yield higher rates, top reaching 77.8%.",
  "Four divergence axes: simulators are (1) too uniform/cooperative in communication style, (2) front-load complete information, (3) lack genuine uncertainty (or over-hedge artificially), and (4) quietly pivot strategy rather than push back on agent errors.",
  "Concrete behavioral gaps: GPT-4o brief turns 1.0% vs 29.0% human; polite turns 49.0% vs 15.3% human; GPT-4o hedges 14.6% vs 7.3% human; simulators pivot on errors ~16.5-19.1% vs 8.4% human; UserLM-8b emits ~4.8 IDs/turn vs 2.6 human.",
  "LLM-judge/evaluator inflation: GPT-5.1 overestimates the assistant's human-likeness by 55% and overall score by 18% of the rating scale (Figure 4 shows about +1.11 on human-likeness), rating robotic responses as natural relative to humans who actually interacted.",
  "Human validation throughout agent development is necessary; current simulators cannot substitute for real users without correcting these biases."
 ],
 "reusable_for_usersimbench": [
  "USI as a template composite metric: adapt the (1/6) or (1/5) aggregation of behavioral + outcome-calibration + evaluative-alignment terms, each normalized to 0-100, for coding-agent user simulation.",
  "Sorensen-Dice human-matching: Dice_m = 2*min(M,H)/(M+H)*100 to score how closely a simulator metric matches the human reference distribution per behavioral metric, then average within dimensions.",
  "Four behavioral dimensions reframed for coding: D1 communication style (verbosity/politeness), D2 information pattern (front-loading full specs/repro steps vs incremental), D3 clarification (asking about ambiguous requirements / expressing uncertainty), D4 error reaction (how user responds when the agent's code fails \u2014 frustration, pushback vs silently restating).",
  "ECE for outcome calibration: bin tasks by difficulty and compare simulator vs human agent-success (test-pass) rates; (1-ECE)*100 measures whether the simulator preserves true task difficulty / success distribution.",
  "Eval term via post-interaction survey MAE: collect human survey ratings (success, efficiency, human-likeness, interaction flow, reuse intent, overall) and measure simulator-condition vs human MAE; Eval=(1-MAE)*100.",
  "Human-study protocol: Prolific recruitment, task-instruction + role-play side panel, web chat with visible agent tool traces, /stop to end, automatic post-task survey; 3 independent batches over the same task set to establish a human-human agreement ceiling.",
  "Inflation-of-success protocol: hold agent + reward function fixed, swap only the user, and report the agent success-rate delta (human vs each simulator) as the inflation measure.",
  "LLM-judge bias audit: compare an LLM evaluator's ratings of interaction quality against ratings from humans who actually performed the interactions, reporting per-dimension over-rating (e.g. human-likeness)."
 ],
 "relevance": "Directly foundational for UserSimBench. It provides (a) a concrete, reimplementable composite metric (USI) for scoring user-simulator fidelity, (b) a validated human-study protocol producing a real-human reference distribution, (c) a behavioral taxonomy (style, information pattern, clarification, error reaction) that transfers to coding-agent users, and (d) explicit evidence + measurement methods for two failure modes we likely care about \u2014 agent-success inflation and LLM-judge over-rating. We can port USI to coding agents by swapping tau-bench customer-service tasks for coding tasks and the binary database-state reward for a test-pass/build reward, keeping the same aggregation, Dice-matching, ECE, and survey-MAE machinery.",
 "uncertainties": [
  "Survey dimension count is reported inconsistently across the paper text and dataset card: variously '6 interaction-quality dimensions' plus task-success+overall (=8) in the main text, but the dataset card lists 10 fields (including open-text behavioral examples and improvement suggestions). The canonical count for the Eval/MAE term (which fields are numeric and included) needs confirmation from the actual JSON.",
  "The exact LIWC/NRC/regex feature definitions per metric and the precise list of metrics inside each of D1-D4 were paraphrased by a fast model; the verbatim feature list and any weighting within a dimension should be confirmed from Section 3 / appendix.",
  "Whether ECE bins are by 'difficulty' or by predicted-success probability, and how bin boundaries are set, is not fully pinned down \u2014 described as difficulty bins but standard ECE uses confidence bins; verify.",
  "Exact per-participant task count and compensation: inferred as ~1 interaction per participant (451 participants, 495 annotations) but the paper does not clearly state tasks-per-participant or Prolific pay rate.",
  "The evaluator-inflation phrasing 'human-likeness by 55% and overall score by 18% of the rating scale' was returned by the summarizer; one fetch instead gave +1.11 (human-likeness) and +0.83 (reuse intent) absolute points. The precise mapping between the percentage figures and absolute point deltas (and which is in the paper text vs Figure 4) should be verified.",
  "Primary agent model is reported as GPT-5.2 (with Gemini-3.1-Pro robustness check); given the 2026 setting this is plausible but unverified beyond the fetched summary.",
  "Dataset reported once as '495 annotated conversations' and the count 451 participants vs 495 annotations vs 165 tasks x 3 batches should be reconciled against the actual file."
 ]
}

